Ionization quenching refers to a reduction in scintillation output resulting from high excitation and ionization densities produced by a recoiling ion in a scintillating medium. Birks proposed the first phenomenological description for organic scintillators in 1951 [36] and this model remains widely used in the literature today. For an ion slowing down along a distance x in the scintillating material, the amount of scintillation light produced, L, is given by:2dLdx=SdEdx1+kBdEdx,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \frac{\text {d}L}{\text {d}x} = \frac{S\,\frac{\text {d}E}{\text {d}x}}{1 + kB\,\frac{\text {d}E}{\text {d}x}}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where dE/dx\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text {d}E/\text {d}x$$\end{document} is the stopping power of the ion in the scintillating medium, S establishes the conversion between light produced and energy deposited in the limit of an unquenched system, and kB\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$kB$$\end{document}, termed the Birks constant, introduces nonlinearity characteristic of ionization quenching. Discrepancies have been observed between the Birks model and measured PLY data, particularly below 1 MeV, for a variety of organic scintillators [13, 37, 38]. More recently, it has been shown that the model fails to accurately describe the PLY of four different samples for energies above 1 MeV when lower energy data are considered [39]. Chou extended the model by introducing a bimolecular quenching term [40] which contributes quadratically with the stopping power:3dLdx=SdEdx1+kBdEdx+CdEdx2.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \frac{\text {d}L}{\text {d}x} = \frac{S\,\frac{\text {d}E}{\text {d}x}}{1 + kB\,\frac{\text {d}E}{\text {d}x}+ C\left( \frac{\text {d}E}{\text {d}x}\right) ^{2}}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Using either model, the total photon yield for a fully stopped ion can be found by numerically integrating the quenching relation using a table of stopping powers.

Quenching parameters are extracted by fitting each model to the measured PLY data via χ2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^{2}$$\end{document} minimization, with χ2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^{2}$$\end{document} defined as:4χ2=∑i,jΔiHijΔj,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
