				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$i{\text {th}}$$\end{document} proton energy bin, respectively; fE;S,kB,C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f\left( E;S,kB,C\right) $$\end{document} denotes the integration of the model up to energy E; and H is the inverse of the covariance matrix of the dataset under consideration. Stopping power tables were generated using the Stopping Range of Ions in Matter (SRIM) software package [41], in which the stopping power of a compound material is calculated as a linear combination of those of its atomic constituents, as suggested by [42]. For table-defined energies E, the integral is performed using the trapezoidal rule. For non-table-defined energies, the yield is computed by linearly interpolating between adjacent table-defined yields. Parameter uncertainties and correlations are computed from the covariance matrix.

The light yields of LABPPO and WbLS as a function of proton recoil energy are shown in Fig. 12 and listed in Tables 4 and 5, respectively. The horizontal error bars denote the energy bin widths and do not represent uncertainty. The relative PLY of WbLS is consistently lower than that of LABPPO by 3.8%, although some energy bins below 9.5 MeV are consistent to within 1σ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
